2. Among the interesting variables in gapminder is life expectancy. How has global life expectancy changed between 1952 and 2007?

gapminder %>% 
  mutate(as.factor(lifeExp)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=lifeExp))+
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method= lm, se=F)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

3. How do the distributions of life expectancy compare for the years 1952 and 2007?

gapminder %>% 
  filter(year=="1952" | year=="2007") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year))+
  geom_bar()

4. Your answer above doesnt tell the whole story since life expectancy varies by region. Make a summary that shows the min, mean, and max life expectancy by continent for all years represented in the data.

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(year, continent) %>% 
  summarize(min_lifeexp=min(lifeExp),
            max_lifeexp=max(lifeExp),
            mean_lifeexp=mean(lifeExp)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=min_lifeexp, fill=continent))+
  geom_col(position = "dodge")
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the

7. Which countries have had the largest population growth since 1952?

gapminder %>%
  select(country, year, pop) %>% 
  filter(year=="1952" | year=="2007") %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = year,
              values_from= pop) %>% 
  rename(yr_1952="1952", yr_2007="2007") %>% 
  mutate(pop_growth = yr_2007-yr_1952) %>% 
  arrange(desc(pop_growth)) %>% 
  filter(pop_growth>=133408087)
## # A tibble: 5  4

8. Use your results from the question above to plot population growth for the top five countries since 1952.

gapminder %>%
  select(country, year, pop) %>% 
  filter(year=="1952" | year=="2007") %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = year,
              values_from= pop) %>% 
  rename(yr_1952="1952", yr_2007="2007") %>% 
  mutate(pop_growth = yr_2007-yr_1952) %>% 
  arrange(desc(pop_growth)) %>% 
  filter(pop_growth>=133408087) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=country, y=pop_growth, fill=country))+
  geom_col()+ 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "YlOrBr") +
  theme_light()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust=1))+
  labs(title="Population Growth since 1952")

9. How does per capita GDP growth compare between these same five countries?

gapminder %>%
  mutate(as.integer(gdpPercap)) %>% 
  select(country, year, gdpPercap) %>% 
  filter(year=="1952" | year=="2007") %>% 
  filter(country=="Brazil"| country=="China" | country=="India" | country=="Indonesia"| country=="United States") %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = year,
              values_from= gdpPercap) %>% 
  rename(yr_1952="1952", yr_2007="2007") %>% 
  mutate(gdp_growth = yr_2007-yr_1952) %>% 
  arrange(desc(gdp_growth)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=country, y=gdp_growth, fill=country))+
  geom_col()+ 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "YlOrBr") +
  theme_light()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, hjust=1))+
  labs(title="GDP Growth since 1952")
